description:
Due to limitations in current experimental approaches, the physiological role of microbial interactions in a mammalian gut microbiome remains poorly understood. Thus, to explore the consequences of bacterial antagonism in this environment, we characterized a wild murine gut microbiome, WildR. This microbiome was initially obtained from wild mice and reconstituted in germ-free laboratory mice in 2017 (Rosshart, et al. 2017 Cell. PMID: 29056339). To identify the speices present in this community, which has since been propogated for multiple generations, we performed long and short-read metagenomic sequencing and assembled metagenome-assembled genomes using a hybrid assembly approach of the current F7 generation. These MAGs facilitated identification of the community composition along with systems involved in microbial interactions.&nbsp; 
 MAG sequences are uploaded as fasta files or with annotations from Prokka as genbank files.&nbsp; 

 Fasta files containing contigs for each genome: WildR-MAG-fasta.tar.gz (0.25 GB) 
 Prokka-annotated MAGs: WildR-MAG-prokka-genbank.tar.gz (0.45 GB) 

 Assembly metrics and taxonomic annotations for each MAG are also uploaded.&nbsp; 

 Assembly metrics: Table1-WildR-MAG-metrics.xlsx (50 KB) 
 Taxonomic annotation: Table1-WildR-MAG-metrics.tsv (230 KB)

